# Solution

This is a relatively straightforward problem. It is almost identical to the first problem in Project Euler.

First, let's find all 4-digit palindromes. We can do that by generating all 4-digit numbers and checking whether they are palindromes. The easiest way to do that is to generate all 4-digit numbers in ascending order, then check whether they are palindromes.

To generate all 4-digit numbers in ascending order, we can use a loop. For each digit, we generate all possible values from 0 to 9, and then concatenate them to form the next number.

The code to generate all 4-digit numbers in ascending order is as follows:

#include <iostream>

int main() {
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
std::cout << i << std::endl;
}
}


The code above generates all 4-digit numbers in ascending order. It uses a for loop to generate all possible values for the first digit, then all possible values for the second digit, and so on.

The code to check whether a number is a palindrome is as follows:

bool isPalindrome(int number) {
std::string str = std::to_string(number);
std::string rev = str;
std::reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());
return str == rev;
}


The code above uses std::to_string to convert the number to a string, then uses std::reverse to reverse the string. Finally, it compares the original string with the reversed string to check whether the number is a palindrome.

The final step is to sum all the palindromic numbers. We can do that by looping through all the numbers and checking whether they are palindromes. If they are, we add them to the sum.

The code to sum all the palindromic numbers is as follows:

int sum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
if (isPalindrome(i)) {
sum += i;
}
}


The code above loops through all the numbers from 0 to 9999. For each number, it checks whether it is a palindrome using the isPalindrome function. If it is, it adds it to the sum.

The final step is to print the sum.

The complete code is as follows:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>

bool isPalindrome(int number) {
std::string str = std::to_string(number);
std::string rev = str;
std::reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());
return str == rev;
}

int main() {
int sum = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
if (isPalindrome(i)) {
sum += i;
}
}
std::cout << "Sum of all 4-digit palindromes: " << sum << std::endl;
return 0;
}


